The code block provided is:

```cpp
int main() {
    Simple obj;
    Simple* ptr;
    ptr = &obj;
    cout << obj.ar;
    cout << ptr->ar;
}
```

In this code, a constructor for the `Simple` class is not explicitly defined. This means that the compiler will automatically generate a default constructor for the class.

When an object of type `Simple` is created using the statement `Simple obj;`, the default constructor is called to initialize the object. The default constructor initializes the data member `a` in the `Simple` class.

The pointer `ptr` is then assigned the address of the object `obj` using the statement `ptr = &obj;`. This means that `ptr` now points to the same memory location as `obj`.

When we try to access the data member `ar` through both `obj` and `ptr`, it will behave in the same way because they point to the same memory location. The output of the program will be the value of `a` printed twice.

However, if there was a constructor defined for the `Simple` class that initializes `a` with a specific value, then the behavior of the pointer `ptr` would be different when assigned to point to an object of the same class. In this case, the constructor would be called when the object is created, and the value of `a` would be initialized accordingly.

Therefore, the use of constructors in the `Simple` class affects the behavior of the pointer `ptr` by determining the initial value of the data member `a`.
